habitat_description:
The Baja California treefrog occupies chaparral, woodland, desert oases, and grass lands of southern California, northeastern Arizona, and southern Nevada (Green et al. 2014; Patterson et al. 2003). Cover is provided by crevices, rodent burrows, under bark, and in the vegetation along streams, but also can be found away from water when not in the breeding season. A limited number of sightings have been reported in southern California; Bakersfield, Santa Barbara county, and on Santa Cruz, Santa Catalina, and Santa Rosa Islands (californiaherps.com).


SW	-Cover is associated with vegetation along streams and rock fissures in proximity to water (Green et al. 2014).
